{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20141203023917|636406769","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Adam_Smith_(politician)","to":"Adam Smith (politician)"}],"pages":{"410158":{"pageid":410158,"ns":0,"title":"Adam Smith (politician)","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2014-12-28T09:10:52Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Other people|Adam Smith}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Adam Smith\n|image         = Profile adam smith.JPG\n|state         = [[Washington (state)|Washington]]\n|district      = {{ushr|Washington|9|9th}}\n|term_start    = January 3, 1997\n|term_end      = \n|predecessor   = [[Randy Tate]]\n|successor     = \n|state_senate1 = Washington\n|district1     = [[Washington's 33rd legislative district|33rd]]\n|term_start1   = January 3, 1991\n|term_end1     = January 3, 1997\n|predecessor1  = Eleanor Lee\n|successor1    = [[Julia Patterson]]\n|birth_name    = David Adam Smith\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1965|6|15}}\n|birth_place   = [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse        = Sara Smith\n|children      = 2\n|alma_mater    = [[Western Washington University]]<br>[[Fordham University]]<br>[[University of Washington School of Law|University of Washington, Seattle]]\n|religion      = [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopalianism]]\n|website       = [http://adamsmith.house.gov/ House website]\n}}\n'''David Adam Smith''' (born June 15, 1965), [[United States|American]] politician, has been a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] since 1997, representing [[Washington's 9th congressional district]].\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Washington, D.C.]] and raised in the [[SeaTac, Washington|Sea-Tac]] area of [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]] State, Smith was adopted as an infant by Lelia June (n\u00e9e Grant) and his maternal uncle Ben Martin Smith III.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adamsmith.house.gov/biography/ |title=U.S. Congressman Adam Smith biography|publisher=Office of U.S. Congressman Adam Smith |date= |accessdate=2014-09-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/reps/smithadam.htm |title=Adam Smith ancestry |publisher=Freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com |date= |accessdate=2014-09-06}}</ref> He attended Bow Lake Elementary and Chinook Middle School, before graduating from [[Tyee Educational Complex|Tyee High School]] in 1983. While in high school Smith participated in the [[Close Up Foundation|Close Up Washington]] civic education program. His father, who worked for [[United Airlines]] as a ramp serviceman and was active in the [[International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers|Machinists' Union]], died when Smith was 19.<ref>\"Remarks by Representative Adam Smith (D-WA) at the Democratic National Convention, July 27, 2004,\" where he said:  \"It was only because of my father's union and the benefits he had worked a lifetime to secure that my family could continue to pay the bills so that I could finish my education.\" [http://zinger.vote-smart.org/public-statement/55613/remarks-by-representative-adam-smith-d-wa-at-the-democratic-national-convention]</ref>\n\nSmith attended [[Western Washington University]] in [[Bellingham, Washington|Bellingham]] for a year, later graduating from [[Fordham University]] in 1987 with a bachelor's degree in [[political science]]. He completed a [[Juris Doctor]] (J.D.) degree at the [[University of Washington]] in 1990. He worked his way through college by loading trucks for [[United Parcel Service]]. After law school, Smith worked as a private practice attorney with Cromwell, Mendozza, and Belur. From 1993 to 1995, he served as a [[prosecutor]] for the city of [[Seattle]]. In 1996, he worked temporarily as a ''pro tem'' judge.\n\nIn 1993, Adam married Spokane native, Sara Bickle-Eldridge, a graduate of the University of Washington and Seattle University School of Law. Their daughter, Kendall, was born in July 2000, followed by their son, Jack, in June 2003.\n\n==Politics==\nSmith served in the [[Washington State Senate]] from 1991 to 1997. He was just twenty-five years old at the time of his election in 1990, defeating a 13-year incumbent [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], Eleanor Lee, to become the youngest [[State Senator]] in the country. Smith won his seat in the U.S. House of Representatives in 1996 by defeating another incumbent Republican, religious conservative [[Randy Tate]]. Smith hasn't faced serious opposition since, and turned what was originally drawn as a \"fair fight\" district into a fairly safe Democratic seat. \n\nSmith's district was significantly redrawn after the 2010 census.  It absorbed much of southeast Seattle, as well as most of the [[Eastside (King County, Washington)|Eastside]].  As a result, it became the state's first with a majority of residents who are racial or ethnic minorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/editorials/2018755554_edit24congninth.html | title=Re-elect U.S. Rep. Adam Smith in Washington's 9th Congressional District | publisher=Seattle Times | date=July 23, 2012 | accessdate=October 5, 2012 }}</ref>  It is also the second-most Democratic district in the state; only the neighboring [[Washington's 7th congressional district|7th district]] is more Democratic.  For the 2012 election, Smith moved from his longtime home in [[Tacoma]] to [[Bellevue, Washington|Bellevue]].\n\n[[File:Smith and obama key arena 2008.jpg|thumb|250px|Adam Smith and [[Barack Obama]] at a campaign rally at [[Seattle]]'s [[KeyArena]], 8 Feb 2008.]]\n\nHe has been a leader in [[moderate]], \"[[New Democrat]]\" organizations. He serves as the chair of the [[political action committee]] of the [[New Democrat Coalition]].\n\nOn October 10, 2002, Adam Smith was among the 81 Democratic members of the House voting in favor of authorizing the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|invasion of Iraq]].<ref>http://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/107-2002/h455</ref>\nIn March 2012, Smith said that US troops had done \u201camazing work\u201d in Afghanistan and that it was \u201ctime to bring the troops home.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.thenewstribune.com/politics/2012/03/20/u-s-rep-adam-smith-joins-calls-to-bring-troops-home-from-afghanistan/ | title=U.S. Rep. Adam Smith joins calls to bring troops home from Afghanistan | publisher=The News Tribune | date=March 20, 2012 | accessdate=October 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Smith won his sixth term in Congress. His opponent was Republican [[Steve Cofchin]]. Smith won 65.7% of the vote to Cofchin's 34.3%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vote.wa.gov/elections/general/Results.aspx?o=b74ba317-0b75-4caf-9f4d-6256f5a2e281 |title=2006 General Election Results |publisher=Vote.wa.gov |date= |accessdate=2012-01-06}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2007, Smith threw his support behind Senator [[Barack Obama]] for the [[United States presidential election, 2008|2008 Presidential Election]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Connelly |first=Joel |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/connelly/311514_joel13.html |title=Obama lands a key backer in Adam Smith |publisher=seattlepi.com |date=2007-04-12 |accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref> He has also appeared on ''[[Hardball with Chris Matthews]]'' speaking for Obama. In the same year he also appeared on the Colbert Report, in the show's 434 part series known as \"Better Know A District\". \n\nSmith voted against the [[Protect America Act of 2007]], which has been criticized for violating American citizens' civil liberties by allowing for wiretapping without issued warrants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h2007-836 |title=GovTrack: House Vote On Passage: S. 1927 [110th&#93;: Protect America Act of 2007 |publisher=Govtrack.us |date=2007-08-04 |accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref> However, Smith voted in favor of the 2001 [[Patriot Act]] and in favor of extending the \u201cBush administration's warrantless wiretapping program.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/adam-smith-d-wash/gIQAiu9RKP_topic.html#the-issues | title=Adam Smith (D-Wash.) | publisher=The Washington Post | accessdate=October 5, 2012 | date=July 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Smith won a seventh term in the House by defeating James Postma, a 74-year-old retired engineer running on a pro-nuclear power platform, with 65% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/2008/results/individual/#mapHWA/H/09 |title=Local and National Election Results - Election Center 2008 - Elections & Politics from |publisher=CNN.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref>\n\nOn December 16, 2010, Smith defeated [[Silvestre Reyes]] and [[Loretta Sanchez]] to become the Ranking Member of the [[House Armed Services Committee]] after Chairman [[Ike Skelton]] was defeated for re-election.  In the first round, Sanchez and Smith earned 64 votes with Reyes earning 53.  In the runoff, Smith defeated Sanchez by 11 votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1210/46528.html |title=Adam Smith wins Armed Services post - Jen DiMascio |publisher=Politico.Com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, recognized for his work in fighting global poverty, Smith became only the second member of Congress selected to the [[Borgen Project]]'s Board of Directors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://borgenproject.blogspot.com/2011/08/congressman-adam-smith-joins-borgen.html |title=selected to The Borgen Project's Board of Directors |publisher=Borgenproject.blogspot.com |date=2011-08-21 |accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref> In the same year, Smith argued against cuts that could \u201cjeopardize our national security\u201d which could leave the US  \u201cmore vulnerable to nuclear terrorism.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/congress-blog/economy-a-budget/146745-funding-cuts-jeopardize-nuclear-non-proliferation | title=Funding cuts jeopardize nuclear non-proliferation | publisher=The Hill | date= 03/01/11 | accessdate=October 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:US Congressman Adam Smith (born 1965).jpg|thumb|Smith as a representative]]In 2001, Congress passed the Authorization for Use of Military Force (AUMF),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lamarledger.com/lamar-news/ci_20204933/county-commissioners-hear-from-concerned-citizens?source=most_viewed |title=County Commissioners hear from Concerned Citizens |publisher=Lamarledger.com |date=2012-03-19 |accessdate=2012-03-19}}</ref> which gave the President authority to use \u201call necessary and appropriate force\u201d against those who committed and aided the 9/11 attacks. While this power has been rarely used to detain persons in the United States, Smith introduced a bill to ensure that any individual detained on U.S. soil under the AUMF has access to due process and the federal court system.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2017741087_detention14m.html |title=Smith proposes bill seeking to try terror suspects in civilian courts |publisher=SeattleTimes.com |date=2012-03-13 |accessdate=2012-03-03 |first=Kyung M. |last=Song}}</ref> The bill also prohibits military commissions and indefinite detention for individuals detained in the United States and affirms that any trial proceedings \u201cshall have all the due process as provided for under the Constitution.\u201d\n\nThe congressman co-sponsored, with Republican congressman [[Mac Thornberry]], an amendment to the fiscal 2013 defense spending bill reversing previous bans on disseminating Defense and State Department propaganda in the United States, reversing the Smith-Mundt Act of 1948 and the Foreign Relations Authorization Act of 1987, designed to protect U.S. audiences from government misinformation campaigns.<ref>http://www.buzzfeed.com/mhastings/congressmen-seek-to-lift-propaganda-ban</ref> The bill passed on May 18, 2012 with 299 to 120.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/house-approves-6425billion-defense-bill/2012/05/18/gIQAkJnYZU_story.html | work=The Washington Post | first=Walter | last=Pincus | title=National Security | date=2012-05-19}}</ref>\n\n===Issues===\n* Smith voted to approve the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|invasion of Iraq]].<ref>http://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/107-2002/h455</ref>\n* Smith voted to approve the controversial [[Cyber Intelligence Sharing and Protection Act]] (CISPA) <ref>http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2013/roll117.xml</ref>\n* Smith voted against an amendment that would restrict the [[National Security Agency]] from collecting phone records of Americans suspected of no crimes without a warrant  <ref>http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2013/roll412.xml</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]]''' (Ranking Member)\n\n**As the ranking member on the committee, Rep. Smith may serve as an ''ex officio'' member of all subcommitees.\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n\n*21st Century Healthcare Caucus\n\n*European Union Caucus\n\n*Goods Movement Caucus\n\n*Intellectual Property Caucus (Co-Chair)\n\n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus|International Conservation Caucus]]\n\n*Waterways Caucus\n\n*Congressional Arts Caucus\n\n==Wikipedia editing==\n\nSmith was among 32 Congressmen who have favorably edited their own Wikipedia entries. Smith admitted that \u201cdefending himself and his record against false attacks was the main reason for the edits, and that the edits were made on just three occasions and unrelated to any re-election effort.\u201d Smith's communications director confirmed that they had made \u201cseveral changes\u201d and were unaware of Wikipedia guidelines highlighting possible conflicts of interests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mercerisland.patch.com/articles/rep-adam-smith-staffers-caught-editing-wikipedia-page | title=Rep. Adam Smith Staffers Caught Editing Wikipedia Page | publisher=MercerIslandPatch | date=July 10, 2012 | accessdate=October 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n\n*[[Washington United States House elections, 2006]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* ''The Almanac of American Politics 2004''. Washington, D.C.: National Journal, 2003.\n* ''Pierce County Official Local Voters' Pamphlet'' (Pierce County Auditor, 2012).\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Adam Smith (politician)}}\n*[http://www.house.gov/adamsmith/ Congressman Adam Smith] official U.S. House site\n*[http://www.electadamsmith.com/ Adam Smith for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Washington/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Adam_Smith_%5BD-9%5D|Adam Smith}}\n{{CongLinks | congbio = s000510 | ballot = Adam_Smith | nndb = 466/000040346 | votesmart = 845 | govtrack = 400379 | opencong = 400379 | rollcall = 520 | politifact = | fec = H6WA09025 | opensecrets = N00007833 | assets = adam-smith | legistorm = 483/Rep_Adam_Smith.html | ontheissues = House/David_Adam_Smith.htm | congress = adam-smith/1528 | worldcat = | c-span = adamsmith | imdb = 2683584 | bloomberg = | nyt = | washpo = gIQAiu9RKP }}\n*[http://www.theyoungturks.com/story/2008/3/27/203554/807/ John Adams Interview with The Young Turks]{{deadlink|date=March 2014}}\n*[http://newsvac.newsforge.com/newsvac/02/10/23/1247236.shtml?tid=4 Letter to Dick Clarke] October 23, 2002{{deadlink|date=March 2014}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s